## Decision 10: Same routes, different ports (no V2 versioning)
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** The old project (with the fat JWT and old tables) runs
on port 5969 and continues to serve users during this migration. The
new project is being built in parallel.
**Old approach considered:** Introduce versioned API routes (/api/v1
for the old, /api/v2 for the new) in a single FastAPI app, with a
feature flag to control which routes are exposed.
**New approach:** The new project runs as a SEPARATE service on
port 5970 with its own codebase. Both services share the same
database but read from different table sets (old tables vs. dpah_*
tables). API routes keep the same /api/v1/* prefix in both services
because they are physically separate — there is no risk of collision.
The frontend chooses which service to talk to by base URL (port).
**Why this is better:** Cleanest possible isolation. Rollback is
operational ("stop the new service") rather than code-level. No
feature flags, no dual-route handling, no risk of contamination
between the two systems.
**Trade-offs:** Two services to deploy and monitor. Database state
must remain compatible with both for the duration of the migration.
**Industry pattern reference:** Blue-green deployment with shared
data layer. Closely related to the strangler fig pattern (Decision 12).
**Where it lives in code:** Operational concern — see deployment
configuration. New service runs on port 5970 via VS Code launch
configuration.

